{"cursor":"72593","size":15,"audio":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/93/Thunder.ogg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d6/LightningCNP.ogg"],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n{{multiple issues|\n\n|disputed = August 2012|contradict = August 2012}}\n\n]]\n\n'Lightning' is a massive electrostatic discharge caused by unbalanced electric\ncharges in the atmosphere, and resulting in a strike, from a cloud to itself,\na cloud to a cloud or a cloud to ground, and accompanied by the loud sound of\nthunder. A typical cloud to ground lightning strike jumps a 5 km\n(3 mi) gap through the air. Uman, Martin A.' \"All About Lightning\";\np. 81; Dover Publications N.Y.; 1986; ISBN- 2-486-25237-x A typical\nthunderstorm has three or more strikes per minute at its peak. Uman,\nMartin A.' \"All About Lightning\"; p. 55; Dover Publications N.Y.; 1986; ISBN-\n2-486-25237-x\n\nLightning is usually produced by cumulonimbus clouds based 5â6 km (3-\n4 mi) above the ground and that are themselves up to 15 km (9 mi)\nin height. Lightning also occurs during snow storms (thundersnow), volcanic\neruptions, dust storms, forest fires or tornadoes. [http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2010/02/100203-\nvolcanoes-lightning/ New Lightning Type Found Over Volcano?].\nNews.nationalgeographic.com (February 2010). Retrieved on June 23,\n2012. Hurricanes typically generate some lightning, mainly in\nthe rainbands as much as 160 km (100 mi) from the\ncenter. Hurricane lightning [http://nldr.library.ucar.edu/repository/assets/soars/SOARS-000-000-000-\n193.pdf] Accesssed 27 Jul 2012 Hurricane Lightning [http://science.nasa.gov/science-news/science-at-\nnasa/2006/09jan_electrichurricanes/] Accessed 17 Jul 2012 Long Range\nLightning Detection Network [http://www.unidata.ucar.edu/committees/polcom/2009-\nspring/statusreports/BusingerS09.pdf] Accessed 27 Jul 2012\n\nWhen the local electric field exceeds the dielectric strength of damp air (about\n3 million volts per meter), electrical discharge results in a strike, often\nfollowed by commensurate discharges branching from the same path. (See image,\nright.) Mechanisms that cause the charges to build up to lightning are still a\nmatter of scientific investigation.\nLightning may be caused by the circulation of warm moisture-filled air through\nelectric fields. Uman, Martin A.' \"All About Lightning\"; p. 61; Dover\nPublications N.Y.; 1986; ISBN- 2-486-25237-x Ice or water particles then\naccumulate charge as in a Van de Graaff generator. Rakov, Vladimir and Uman,\nMartin; \"Lightning: Physics and Effects\"; Cambridge University Press (January 8,\n2007);p. 84;ISBN 978-0521035415\n\nThe science of lightning is called [[fulminology]]. [http://www.wcl.govt.nz/blogs/kids/index.php/2008/07/17/a-\nfulminologist-is-a/ A Fulminologist is aâ¦]. Wcl.govt.nz (2008-07-17). Retrieved\non June 23, 2012. The fear of lightning is called astraphobia.\n\n]] , Utah, United States.]]\n","linknr":1201,"url":"Lightning","recorded":1362485586,"links":153,"instances":["satellite","lightning","meteorology","rune","sailplane","number","phenomenon","benedictine","radio"],"pdf":["http://nldr.library.ucar.edu/repository/assets/soars/SOARS-000-000-000-193.pdf","http://www.unidata.ucar.edu/committees/polcom/2009spring/statusreports/BusingerS09.pdf","http://www.easa.europa.eu/safety-and-research/research-projects/docs/large-aeroplanes/EASA.2008_5.pdf","http://www.easa.europa.eu/safety-and-research/research-projects/docs/large-aeroplanes/EASA.2008_5.pdf","https://www.llnl.gov/str/pdfs/05_96.1.pdf","http://www.lightningtech.com/pdfs/A_PROPOSED_ADDITION_TO_LIGHTNING_ENVIRONMENT_STDS.pdf","http://pubs.usgs.gov/bul/1083e/report.pdf","http://web.archive.org/web/20061003193325/http://lep694.gsfc.nasa.gov/gunther/gunther/Wasilewski1999.pdf","http://web.archive.org/web/20061003193325/http://lep694.gsfc.nasa.gov/gunther/gunther/Wasilewski1999.pdf","http://www.osti.gov/energycitations/servlets/purl/823201-oEL59M/native/823201.pdf","http